## Review & Model

- Recall that our objective is to determine the circumstances under which the fertilizer plant is a "good idea"

- My model is based on Ciccone & Matsuyama (1996)

- Emphasizes "vertical complementarity" between intermediate and final goods industries

- Contrast with horizontal complementarity of Rosenstein-Rodan (1943)

---




## Final Good


- One homogenous consumption good (food) 
- Production function:
- $$C=F(X,H)=\underset{X_{1},X_{2},H_{1},H_{2}\geq0}{\max}\left\{ X_{1}^{\alpha}H_{1}^{1-\alpha}+X_{1}^{1-\alpha}H_{1}^{\alpha}\mid X_{1}+X_{2}\leq X,H_{1}+H_{2}\leq H\right\}$$
- X is a composite intermediate good. H is labor. $\alpha \in (0,0.5)$

> - $P=$ Price of X 
- $w=$ Price of H
- $$P>w \implies F(X,H)=X_{1}^{\alpha}H_{1}^{1-\alpha}$$ 
> - $$P < w\implies F(X,H)=X_{1}^{1-\alpha}H_{1}^{\alpha}$$

## Intermediate good $X$

- $X_{t}$ is a composite of differentiated inputs $x_{t}(i)$ at time $t$. CES form:

<!-- continuum of goods --> 

$$X_{t}=\left[\underset{0}{\overset{n_{t}}{\int}}\left[x_{t}(i)\right]^{1-1/\sigma}di\right]^{\sigma/(\sigma-1)}$$

> - But we need discrete inputs:

> - $$X_{t}=\left[\underset{i=1}{\overset{n_{t}}{\sum}}\left[x_{t}(i)\right]^{1-1/\sigma}\right]^{\sigma/(\sigma-1)}$$ 

> - $n_{t}$ is the number of intermediate inputs available in the marketplace at time $t$.

> - $\sigma$ is the direct partial elasticity of substitution between every pair of products. We restrict $\sigma > 1$.
> - Hence higher $n_{t}$ implies greater TFP for final good.

<!-- maybe need to explain --> 



---

## Price of intermediates is decreasing in $n_{t}$

- $P_{t}=n_{t}^{1/(1-\sigma)}w_{t}$

<!-- [skipping some algebra] --> 


Hence:
$$n_{t} < 1 \implies w_{t} < P_{t}$$
$$n_{t} > 1 \implies w_{t} > P_{t}$$

<!-- the n=1 thing is due to how set the unit of intermediate good--> 


---


## Evolution of the economy in $n_{t}-V_{t}$ space

- If the elasticity of substitution between $X$ and $H$ in the final goods production is less than $\sigma$ for all $P_{t}/w_{t}$, then the steady state is guaranteed to be unique.

<!-- which means no development trap --> 

- Let $V_{t}=v_{t}/C_{t}$, where $v_{t}$ is the value of ownership an intermediate goods firm (present discounted value of profits) and $C_{t}$ is final goods production in time $t$.

## What are conditions for multiple steady states?

With the dual technology production function, elasticity of substitution between $X$ and $H$ is $\infty$ when $n_{t}=1$ (and 1 when $n_{t} \neq 1$). Does this guarantee more than one steady state? No.

## We additionally need:

$$\dfrac{\sigma}{1-\sigma}-1<\dfrac{L}{\rho\cdot a_{n}}<\dfrac{\sigma-\alpha}{1-\alpha}$$

Where $\rho$ is the temporal discount rate (let's say $\rho=0.95$), $L$ is the total labor force in the economy, and $a_{n}$ is the labor unit cost of starting up a new firm that produces a new intermediate input variety.

<!-- Note that this "jump point"" at n=1 is a product of a choice of the unit of measurement of x's to get this. we could get the jump point to be at any value of n for a different unit of measurement -->

	     var py = (y-cy)/radius;

	       py = py/plen;

	     gl.vertexAttrib4f( colLoc, 0, 0, 0, 1 );
	     gl.enableVertexAttribArray( texLoc621 );
	     gl.vertexAttribPointer(texLoc621, 2, gl.FLOAT, false, 28, 12);
	     gl.activeTexture(gl.TEXTURE0);
	     gl.bindTexture(gl.TEXTURE_2D, texture621);
	     gl.uniform1i( sampler621, 0);
	     gl.enableVertexAttribArray( ofsLoc621 );
	     gl.vertexAttribPointer(ofsLoc621, 2, gl.FLOAT, false, 28, 20);
	     gl.vertexAttribPointer(posLoc,  3, gl.FLOAT, false, 28,  0);
	     gl.drawElements(gl.TRIANGLES, 6, gl.UNSIGNED_SHORT, 0);
	     // ****** text object 622 *******
	     gl.useProgram(prog622);
	     gl.bindBuffer(gl.ARRAY_BUFFER, buf622);
	     gl.bindBuffer(gl.ELEMENT_ARRAY_BUFFER, ibuf622);
	     gl.uniformMatrix4fv( prMatLoc622, false, new Float32Array(prMatrix.getAsArray()) );
	     gl.uniformMatrix4fv( mvMatLoc622, false, new Float32Array(mvMatrix.getAsArray()) );
	     gl.enableVertexAttribArray( posLoc );
	     gl.disableVertexAttribArray( colLoc );
	     gl.vertexAttrib4f( colLoc, 0, 0, 0, 1 );
	     gl.enableVertexAttribArray( texLoc622 );
	     gl.vertexAttribPointer(texLoc622, 2, gl.FLOAT, false, 28, 12);

	     gl.bindTexture(gl.TEXTURE_2D, texture622);

	   }
	   var vlen = function(v) {
	     return sqrt(v[0]*v[0] + v[1]*v[1] + v[2]*v[2])
	   }
	   var xprod = function(a, b) {
	     return [a[1]*b[2] - a[2]*b[1],
	             a[2]*b[0] - a[0]*b[2],
	             a[0]*b[1] - a[1]*b[0]];
	   }
	   var screenToVector = function(x, y) {
	     var radius = max(width, height)/2.0;
	     var cx = width/2.0;
	     var cy = height/2.0;
	     var px = (x-cx)/radius;
	     var py = (y-cy)/radius;
	     var plen = sqrt(px*px+py*py);
	     if (plen > 1.e-6) { 
	       px = px/plen;
	       py = py/plen;
	     }
	     var angle = (SQRT2 - plen)/SQRT2*PI/2;
	     var z = sin(angle);
	     var zlen = sqrt(1.0 - z*z);
	     px = px * zlen;
	     py = py * zlen;
	     return [px, py, z];
	   }
	   var rotBase;
	   var trackballdown = function(x,y) {
	     rotBase = screenToVector(x, y);
	     saveMat.load(userMatrix);
	   }
	   var trackballmove = function(x,y) {
	     var rotCurrent = screenToVector(x,y);
	     var dot = rotBase[0]*rotCurrent[0] + 
	   	       rotBase[1]*rotCurrent[1] + 
	   	       rotBase[2]*rotCurrent[2];
	     var angle = acos( dot/vlen(rotBase)/vlen(rotCurrent) )*180./PI;
	     var axis = xprod(rotBase, rotCurrent);
	     userMatrix.load(saveMat);
	     userMatrix.rotate(angle, axis[0], axis[1], axis[2]);
	     drawScene();
	   }
	   var y0zoom = 0;
	   var zoom0 = 1;
	   var zoomdown = function(x, y) {
	     y0zoom = y;
	     zoom0 = log(zoom);
	   }
	   var zoommove = function(x, y) {
	     zoom = exp(zoom0 + (y-y0zoom)/height);
	     drawScene();
	   }
	   var y0fov = 0;
	   var fov0 = 1;
	   var fovdown = function(x, y) {
	     y0fov = y;
	     fov0 = fov;
	   }
	   var fovmove = function(x, y) {
	     fov = max(1, min(179, fov0 + 180*(y-y0fov)/height));
	     drawScene();
	   }
	   var mousedown = [trackballdown, zoomdown, fovdown];
	   var mousemove = [trackballmove, zoommove, fovmove];
	   function relMouseCoords(event){
	     var totalOffsetX = 0;
	     var totalOffsetY = 0;
	     var currentElement = canvas;
	     do{
	       totalOffsetX += currentElement.offsetLeft;
	       totalOffsetY += currentElement.offsetTop;
	     }
	     while(currentElement = currentElement.offsetParent)
	     var canvasX = event.pageX - totalOffsetX;
	     var canvasY = event.pageY - totalOffsetY;
	     return {x:canvasX, y:canvasY}
	   }
	   canvas.onmousedown = function ( ev ){
	     if (!ev.which) // Use w3c defns in preference to MS
	       switch (ev.button) {
	       case 0: ev.which = 1; break;
	       case 1: 
	       case 4: ev.which = 2; break;
	       case 2: ev.which = 3;
	     }
	     drag = ev.which;
	     var f = mousedown[drag-1];
	     if (f) {
	       var coords = relMouseCoords(ev);
	       f(coords.x, height-coords.y); 
	       ev.preventDefault();
	     }
	   }    
	   canvas.onmouseup = function ( ev ){	
	     drag = 0;
	   }
	   canvas.onmouseout = canvas.onmouseup;
	   canvas.onmousemove = function ( ev ){
	     if ( drag == 0 ) return;
	     var f = mousemove[drag-1];
	     if (f) {
	       var coords = relMouseCoords(ev);
	       f(coords.x, height-coords.y);
	     }
	   }
	   var wheelHandler = function(ev) {
	     var del = 1.1;
	     if (ev.shiftKey) del = 1.01;
	     var ds = ((ev.detail || ev.wheelDelta) > 0) ? del : (1 / del);
	     zoom *= ds;
	     drawScene();
	     ev.preventDefault();
	   };
	   canvas.addEventListener("DOMMouseScroll", wheelHandler, false);
	   canvas.addEventListener("mousewheel", wheelHandler, false);
	}
